snippet.textDisplay:
I've gotta make an argument for temperance here. As much as I agree you shouldn't force people not to drink just cause you don't agree with it, one of the reasons many women were fighting for temperance was that many women faced domestic abuse at the hands of their drunk husbands. See, drinking alcohol was a long standing tradition for centuries but it was only until the turn of the century that people really started making stronger alcohol. The drinking tradition and patterns stayed the same but now the drinks were stronger and it was impacting the home live of many people. Men would spend the money they made for the day at bars and then there was an increased report of domestic violence, which at the time was legal in many states since societal conventions dictated the man was the rule maker in the home. Women were fighting for their lives and for the lives of women and children impacted by alcoholism.


So the temperance movement was definitely more than just a religion focused push to make alcohol illegal to save the souls of US citizens. There were other factors as well, I suggest watching the Ken Burns documentary on Prohibition, last time I checked it was on Netflix!
